\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linear Advection Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:LinearWaveEquationWithSmoothIC"

\end_inset

Find a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,t)$
\end_inset

 satisfying the linear advection equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pdv{u}{t}+a\pdv{u}{x}=0\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times(t_{0},\infty)\label{eq:LinearWaveEquation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the IC
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We use 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 for the spatial variable at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to distinguish it from the one at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(x_{0},t_{0})=u_{0}(x_{0})\qquad x_{0}\in(-\infty,\infty)\label{eq:SmoothInitialWaveProfile}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in which, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth function for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Prove the solution is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
The characteristic curves
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ curve
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearWaveEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 emanating from 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 form a one-parameter family of parallel straight lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The characteristic curve emanating from 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x(t)$
\end_inset

, is the solution of the following IVP:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\dv{x}{t} & =a\qquad t\in(t_{0},\infty)\\
x(0) & =x_{0}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x-x_{0}}{t-t_{0}}=a\qquad t\in[t_{0},\infty)
\]

\end_inset

If we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 as a varying parameter, then all of these characteristic curves together
 form a one-parameter family of parallel straight lines in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)$
\end_inset

 plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 along any characteristic curve of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearWaveEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Along any characteristic curve, the change rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{u}{t}=\pdv{u}{t}+\dv{x}{t}\pdv{u}{x}=\pdv{u}{t}+a\pdv{u}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The solution of IVP 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "prob:LinearWaveEquationWithSmoothIC"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{u=u_{0}(x-(t-t_{0})a)}\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times[t_{0},\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This solution has a clear physical interpretation: a wave packet moving
 with a constant speed, whose shape keeps unchanged.
 Physically, the constant coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 has a dimension of speed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quasilinear Wave Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the wave speed is a non-constant function of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, then IVP 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "prob:LinearWaveEquationWithSmoothIC"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:QuasilinearWaveEquationWithSmoothIC"

\end_inset

Find a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,t)$
\end_inset

 satisfying the PDE
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pdv{u}{t}+a(u)\pdv{u}{x}=0\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times[t_{0},\infty)\label{eq:QuasilinearWaveEquation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the IC 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SmoothInitialWaveProfile"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest case is 
\begin_inset Formula $a(u)=ku$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:InviscidBurgersEquationWithSmoothIC"

\end_inset

Find a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,t)$
\end_inset

 satisfying the PDE
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{t}+ku\pdv{u}{x}=0\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times[t_{0},\infty)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is constant, and the IC 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SmoothInitialWaveProfile"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
When 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

, the PDE is called 
\noun on
inviscid Burgers equation
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
PDE!Burgers equation!inviscid ~
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 could be any physical quantity, while the wave speed 
\begin_inset Formula $ku$
\end_inset

 must has a dimension of speed.
 It is better to keep writing the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, unless 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 has the dimension of speed.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 along any characteristic curve
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ curve
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuasilinearWaveEquation"

\end_inset

 is constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
At least in a finite time period 
\begin_inset Formula $[t_{0},t_{*})$
\end_inset

, the characteristic curves
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
characteristic!~ curve
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuasilinearWaveEquation"

\end_inset

 emanating from 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 form a one-parameter family of straight lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume the characteristic curves do not intersect with each other in 
\begin_inset Formula $[t_{0},t_{*})$
\end_inset

, which will be proved in the section of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "subsec:SmoothSolutionBreaking"

\end_inset

.
 The constancy of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 immediately implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a(u)$
\end_inset

 is also constant along any characteristic curve.
 The characteristic curve emanating from 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},t_{0})$
\end_inset

 is then easily solved to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{x-x_{0}}{t-t_{0}}=a_{0}\label{eq:CharCurveOfQuasilinearWaveEquation-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{0}=a\circ u(x,t)=a\circ u_{0}\circ x_{0}(x,t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, characteristic curves emanated from different initial points are
 
\emph on
no longer parallel
\emph default
 to each other in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The smooth solution of IVP 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "prob:QuasilinearWaveEquationWithSmoothIC"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{u=u_{0}(x-(t-t_{0})a(u))}\qquad(x,t)\in(-\infty,\infty)\times[t_{0},t_{*})\label{eq:SolutionOfQuasilinearWaveEquation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

from which, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can be solved at 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)$
\end_inset

 in principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Breaking of Smooth Solutions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:SmoothSolutionBreaking"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The smooth solution obtained in the previous section is based upon the assumptio
n that characteristic curves 
\emph on
do not intersect
\emph default
 with each other.
 Its validness depends on the positiveness of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{a}{x_{0}}:=\dv{a}{u_{0}}\dv{u_{0}}{x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subset\mathbb{(-\infty,\infty)}$
\end_inset

 is an open interval, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}<q_{0}$
\end_inset

 are two points inside it, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=p(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=q(t)$
\end_inset

 are the equations of the characteristic curves emanating from them, respectivel
y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x_{0}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{a}{x_{0}}>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t\in[t_{0},\infty)$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)<q(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
From 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{x}{t}=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\circ u(x,t)=a\circ u_{0}\left(x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{x}{t}=a\circ u_{0}(x_{0})
\]

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{(q(t)-p(t))}{t}=a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{a}{x_{0}}>0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}p_{0}<q_{0} & \implies a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})>0\\
 & \implies\dv{(q(t)-p(t))}{t}>0
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x_{0}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{a}{x_{0}}<0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists t_{*}>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t_{*})=q(t_{*})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t\in[t_{0},t_{*})$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)<q(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is almost the same as the previous theorem, except for the direction
 of inequality:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{(q(t)-p(t))}{t}=a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})<0
\]

\end_inset

The 
\noun on
intersecting moment
\noun default
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{*}$
\end_inset

 of two characteristic curves emanated from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p_{0},t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q_{0},t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be solved from 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t_{*})=q(t_{*})$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{0}+(t_{*}-t_{0})a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})=q_{0}+(t_{*}-t_{0})a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{*}-t_{0}=-\frac{q_{0}-p_{0}}{a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When two characteristic curves intersect, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 will have two values
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=u_{0}\left(p_{0}\right)\qand u=u_{0}\left(q_{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which are generally inconsistent.
 Such inconsistency will leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv*{u}{x}\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv*{u}{x}$
\end_inset

 can be solved from
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}u & =u_{0}(x-(t-t_{0})a(u))\\
\pdv{u}{x} & =\dv{u_{0}}{x_{0}}\left(1-(t-t_{0})\dv{a}{u}\pdv{u}{x}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{x}=\frac{\dv*{u_{0}}{x_{0}}}{1+(t-t_{0})\dv*{a}{x_{0}}}
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}\in C^{1}(-\infty,\infty)$
\end_inset

, the condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv*{u}{x}\to\infty$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+(t_{*}-t_{0})\dv{a}{x_{0}}=0
\]

\end_inset

which leads to the intersecting moment when the characteristic curve emanated
 from a 
\emph on
specific
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 intersects with some other characteristic curve:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{*}-t_{0}=\frac{-1}{\dv*{a}{x_{0}}}
\]

\end_inset

The 
\noun on
breaking moment
\noun default
 of the smooth solution is the minimum of all these intersecting moments:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{t_{b}-t_{0}=\min_{x_{0}\in\Omega}\left\{ \frac{-1}{\dv*{a}{x_{0}}}\right\} }
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x_{b},t_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 as the IC of a new IVP, it will become a 
\noun on
generalized Riemann problem
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Riemann!~ problem!generalized ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The special case, in which the left and right states are constants, will
 be discussed in the section of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "subsec:RiemannProblems"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

