\begin_layout Theorem
For a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 system, a specialized Riemann invariant 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is constant along any characteristic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{x}{t}=\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\forall i=1,2$
\end_inset

, the parallel relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{L_{i}}\parallel\bra{\grad{\psi}_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{\grad{\psi}_{i}}\Mat{A}=\bra{\grad{\psi}_{i}}\lambda_{i}
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 system of PDEs can then be turned into a pair of ODEs
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mel**{\grad{\psi}_{i}}{\pdv{t}+\lambda_{i}\pdv{x}}{U}=\left(\dv{t}\right)_{i}\psi_{i}=0\qquad i=1,2
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At any point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)$
\end_inset

, we have two algebraic equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eval{\psi_{i}(U_{1},U_{2})}_{(x,t)}=\eval{\psi_{i}(U_{1},U_{2})}_{(x_{0},t_{0})}\qquad i=1,2
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},t_{0})$
\end_inset

 is obtained by tracing back along the characteristic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{x}{t}=\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)$
\end_inset

.
 The original variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U_{1},U_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)$
\end_inset

 can then be solved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[Isentropic Gas Dynamics]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{t}\begin{bmatrix}\rho\\
\rho u
\end{bmatrix}+\pdv{x}\begin{bmatrix}\rho u\\
\rho uu+p
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}\qquad p=C\rho^{\gamma}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
It can be formulated as a quasilinear system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuasilinearHyperbolicSystem1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U}=\begin{bmatrix}\rho\\
\rho u
\end{bmatrix}\qquad\Mat{A(U)}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 1\\
a^{2}-u^{2} & 2u
\end{bmatrix}\qquad a=\sqrt{C\gamma\rho^{\gamma-1}}
\]

\end_inset

The eigenvalues and eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Mat{A}$
\end_inset

 can be found as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\lambda_{1}=u-a\qquad\ket{R_{1}}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\
u-a
\end{bmatrix}\\
\lambda_{2}=u+a\qquad\ket{R_{2}}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\
u+a
\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

The corresponding generalized Riemann invariants can be found from
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\dd{\rho}}{1}=\frac{\dd(\rho u)}{u\mp a}\implies\dd{u}\pm\frac{a}{\rho}\dd{\rho}=0
\]

\end_inset

to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\phi_{1} & =u+\int\frac{a}{\rho}\dd{\rho}=u+\frac{2a}{\gamma-1}\\
\phi_{2} & =u-\int\frac{a}{\rho}\dd{\rho}=u-\frac{2a}{\gamma-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

So, the specialized Riemann invariants are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{1}=\phi_{2}=u-\frac{2a}{\gamma-1}\qquad\psi_{2}=\phi_{1}=u+\frac{2a}{\gamma-1}
\]

\end_inset

Trace along the characteristic curves back to the initial point, we have
 two algebraic equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}u-\frac{2a}{\gamma-1} & =\left(u_{0}-\frac{2a_{0}}{\gamma-1}\right)_{\lambda_{1}=u-a}\\
u+\frac{2a}{\gamma-1} & =\left(u_{0}+\frac{2a_{0}}{\gamma-1}\right)_{\lambda_{2}=u+a}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

from which 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can be solved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discontinuities and Weak Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous sections, we have seen that even with a smooth IC, the smooth
 solution of a quasilinear PDE (system) can finally become discontinuous.
 To handle such cases, we have to extend the notion of solutions to a weaker
 sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conservation Laws
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a 
\noun on
control volume
\noun default
 (CV)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CV"
description "Control Volume"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
control!~ volume
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 is the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, known as a 
\noun on
control surface
\noun default
 (CS)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CS"
description "Control Surface"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
control!~ surface
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{c}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\vec{u}^{c}$"
description "velocity of a point on a control surface"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 is the velocity of a point on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $^{c}$
\end_inset

 stands for 
\bar under
c
\bar default
ontrol volume)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
conservation variable
\noun default
, usually the 
\noun on
density
\noun default
 of some physical quantity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
flux vector
\noun default
, i.e.
 how much such quantity passes through a 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 surface in space per unit area within unit time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the 
\noun on
conservation law
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{V}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{f}\dd{S}=0\label{ConservationLawIntegralForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{t}\int_{V}\phi\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\vec{f}-\phi\vec{u}^{c}\right)\dd{S}=0\label{eq:ConservationLawOnMovingControlVolume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is usually used for 
\emph on
moving
\emph default
 control volumes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth with respect to spatial variables, we can apply Gauss's divergence
 theorem to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "ConservationLawIntegralForm"

\end_inset

, which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{\phi}{t}+\div\vec{f}=0
\]

\end_inset

If the smoothness requirement is not satisfied, we should go back to the
 integral form, which will leads to the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "subsec:JumpConditions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
For a vector conservation law, or a system of conservation laws, we use
 a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 for the conservation variables, a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}:=\ip{i}{U}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
In 3D space, we use a column matrix of vectors (or tensors) 
\begin_inset Formula $\VecKet{F}$
\end_inset

 for the flux, which can be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\VecKet{F}=\sum_{k=1}^{3}\vu{e}_{k}\ket{F_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 The conservation law is then written in one of the following forms
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{t}\int_{V}\ket{U}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\VecKet{F}-\vec{u}^{c}\ket{U}\right)\dd{S}=\ket{0}\label{eq:ConservationLawSystemOnMovingControlVolume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V}\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\VecKet{F}\dd{S}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}+\div{\VecKet{F}}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset

In Cartesian coordinates, the last one is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}+\sum_{k=1}^{3}\pdv{\ket{F_{k}}}{x_{k}}=\ket{0}}\label{eq:SystemOfConservationLaws3d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
In 1D space, only one component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\VecKet{F}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero, so the subscripts can be ignored.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SystemOfConservationLaws3d"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}+\pdv{\ket{F}}{x}=\ket{0}}\label{eq:SystemOfConservationLaws1d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
Scalar conservation laws are just special cases of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SystemOfConservationLaws3d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SystemOfConservationLaws1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phantom{U}}$
\end_inset

 can be ignored.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Jump Conditions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:JumpConditions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is a discontinuity manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 moving with velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{u}^{S}=\vu{e}_{\perp}u_{\perp}^{S}+\vu{e}_{\parallel}u_{\parallel}^{S}
\]

\end_inset

Choose a cylindrical control volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the following requirements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It has an infinitesimal height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, which means
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}\vec{u}^{c}=\vec{u}^{S}\qquad\lim_{h\to0}\dv{t}\int_{V}\ket{U}\dd{V}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All of its walls are 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sandwiched between the top surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}=\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) and the bottom surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}=-\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}\parallel S\parallel S_{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the conservation law on a moving control volume 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLawSystemOnMovingControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is reduced to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S_{+}\cup S_{-}}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\VecKet{F}-\vec{u}^{S}\ket{U}\right)\dd{S}=0
\]

\end_inset

Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{S_{\pm}}\dd{S}\to0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\left(\ket{U_{+}}-\ket{U_{-}}\right)s=\vu{e}_{\perp}\cdot\left(\ket*{\vec{F}_{+}}-\ket*{\vec{F}_{-}}\right)}\qquad s:=\vu{e}_{\perp}\cdot\vec{u}^{S}
\]

\end_inset

which is known as the 
\noun on
Rankine–Hugoniot condition
\noun default
, a.k.a.
 the 
\noun on
jump condition
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a system of conservation laws in 1D space, it becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\ket{U_{+}}-\ket{U_{-}}\right)s=\ket{F_{+}}-\ket{F_{-}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a single conservation law in 1D space, it becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(U_{+}-U_{-}\right)s=F_{+}-F_{-}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Weak Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[Weak Solution of Single Conservation Law]
\end_layout

\end_inset

If there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 integrable function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,t)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & \int_{0}^{+\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\left(\pdv{\phi}{t}u+\pdv{\phi}{x}f\right)\dd{x}\dd{t}\\
+ & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\phi(x_{0},0)u_{0}(x_{0})\dd{x_{0}}\\
= & 0
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\emph on
compact supported smooth
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x,t)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is said to be a weak solution of the single conservation law in 1D space
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SingleConservationLaw1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with the 
\emph on
piecewise smooth
\emph default
 IC
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x_{0},0)=u_{0}(x_{0})\qquad x_{0}\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Any smooth solution is also a weak solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For smooth solutions, we can move the temporal derivative from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & \int_{0}^{+\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\pdv{\phi}{t}u\dd{x}\dd{t}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{+\infty}\left(-\phi\pdv{u}{t}+\pdv{\phi u}{t}\right)\dd{t}\dd{x}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{u}{t}\dd{t}\dd{x}+\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\eval{\phi u}_{0}^{+\infty}\dd{x}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{u}{t}\dd{t}\dd{x}-\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\phi(x_{0},0)u_{0}(x_{0})\dd{x_{0}}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

We drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $t=+\infty$
\end_inset

 term since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t=+\infty,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Similarly, we can move the spatial derivative from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & \int_{0}^{+\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\pdv{\phi}{x}f\dd{x}\dd{t}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{+\infty}\left(-\phi\pdv{f}{x}+\pdv{\phi f}{x}\right)\dd{t}\dd{x}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{f}{x}\dd{t}\dd{x}+\int_{0}^{+\infty}\eval{\phi f}_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\dd{t}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{f}{x}\dd{t}\dd{x}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

We drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm\infty$
\end_inset

 terms since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,x=\pm\infty)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Substitute them into the definition of weak solution, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{0}^{+\infty}-\phi\left(\pdv{u}{t}+\pdv{f}{x}\right)\dd{t}\dd{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

which leads to the PDE since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is chosen arbitrarily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Entropy Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematically, there might be more than one weak solutions.
 However, for a problem with physical backgrounds, there is only one solution,
 which satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the PDE in smooth regions,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
jump conditions across discontinuities,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
entropy conditions across discontinuities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a single conservation law in 1D space, the entropy condition is given
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Lax"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Lax"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(u_{-})\ge s\ge a(u_{+})
\]

\end_inset

which has a clear geometric interpretation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
Characteristic curves near the discontinuity curve must run into or at least
 be parallel with it as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a system of conservation law, the entropy condition is given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\lambda_{k}(U_{-})\ge s & \ge\lambda_{k}(U_{+})\\
\lambda_{k-1}(U_{-})<s & <\lambda_{k+1}(U_{+})
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:EntropyConditionForSystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the terminology of gas dynamics, we can classify various discontinuities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the entropy condition takes an equal sign, it implies a 
\noun on
contact discontinuity
\noun default
, which means there is no mass/momentum/energy flowing through the discontinuity
 surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the entropy condition takes a strict unequal sign, it implies a 
\noun on
shock wave
\noun default
, across which entropy is strictly increased.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Riemann Problems
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:RiemannProblems"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "RP"
description "Riemann Problem"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Riemann!~ problem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without loss of generality, we shall shift the initial discontinuity to
 
\begin_inset Formula $(t=0,x=0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[RP for Single Conservation Law]
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Riemann problem for a single conservation law in 1D space is the IVP
 defined by PDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SingleConservationLaw1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the following IC:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(0,x)=\begin{cases}
u_{-}^{0}, & x<0\\
u_{+}^{0}, & x>0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{+}^{0}$
\end_inset

 are two constants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[RP for Conservation Law System]
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Riemann problem for a system of conservation laws in 1D space is the
 IVP defined by PDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SystemOfConservationLaws1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the following IC:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U(0,x)}=\begin{cases}
\ket{U_{-}^{0}}, & x<0\\
\ket{U_{+}^{0}}, & x>0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

in which, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U_{-}^{0}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U_{+}^{0}}$
\end_inset

 are two constant column matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[Self-Similarity]
\end_layout

\end_inset

If the two independent variables are scaled with the same constant:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,t)\to(\alpha t,\alpha x)\qquad\forall\alpha\ne0
\]

\end_inset

the PDE and IC do not change, then such IVP is said to be 
\noun on
self-similar
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
The solution of a self-similar IVP depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $x/t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
