\begin_layout Theorem
Riemann problems are self-similar and their solutions depend only on 
\begin_inset Formula $x/t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
RP for Linear Wave Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,t)=\begin{cases}
u_{-}^{0}, & x/t<a\\
u_{+}^{0}, & x/t>a
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
On the discontinuity curve 
\begin_inset Formula $x/t=a$
\end_inset

, the PDE is not satisfied.
 Instead, the jump condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\Delta u=\Delta f
\]

\end_inset

and the entropy condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(u_{-})=s=a(u_{+})
\]

\end_inset

are satisfied, in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=a\qquad\Delta u=u_{+}-u_{-}\qquad\Delta f=au_{+}-au_{-}
\]

\end_inset

They are all contact discontinuities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
RP for Linear Hyperbolic System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like in the smooth case, the first step is to project the IC onto the space
 spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{R_{i}}\right\} _{i=1}^{m}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U_{-}^{0}}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}\ket{R_{i}}\ip{L_{i}}{U_{-}^{0}}\qquad\ket{U_{+}^{0}}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}\ket{R_{i}}\ip{L_{i}}{U_{+}^{0}}
\]

\end_inset

The IVP then becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 independent RPs for linear wave equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{V_{i}}{t}+\lambda_{i}\pdv{V_{i}}{x}=0\qquad V_{i}(0,x)=\begin{cases}
\ip{L_{i}}{U_{-}^{0}}, & x<0\\
\ip{L_{i}}{U_{+}^{0}}, & x>0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

We know their solutions are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{i}(x,t)=\begin{cases}
\ip{L_{i}}{U_{-}^{0}}, & x/t<\lambda_{i}\\
\ip{L_{i}}{U_{+}^{0}}, & x/t>\lambda_{i}
\end{cases}\qquad i=1,\dots,m
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution of the original RP is then the 
\emph on
superposition
\emph default
 of all the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 independent waves carrying the initial jump.
 Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th wave propagates with speed 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

, so the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)$
\end_inset

 plane is divided into 
\begin_inset Formula $(m+1)$
\end_inset

 regions by the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 straight characteristic curves.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th region where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}<x/t<\lambda_{k+1}$
\end_inset

, we know that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the jumps in the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 waves are to the 
\emph on
left
\emph default
 of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x/t\in(\lambda_{k},\lambda_{k+1})$
\end_inset

, so these waves contributes their 
\emph on
right
\emph default
 values;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the jumps in the other 
\begin_inset Formula $(m-k)$
\end_inset

 waves are to the 
\emph on
right
\emph default
 of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x/t\in(\lambda_{k},\lambda_{k+1})$
\end_inset

, so these waves contributes their 
\emph on
left
\emph default
 values;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x/t\in(\lambda_{k},\lambda_{k+1})$
\end_inset

 (except on the discontinuities) is the superposition of them:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\ket{U(x,t)} & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}\ket{R_{i}}\ip{L_{i}}{U_{+}^{0}}+\sum_{i=k+1}^{m}\ket{R_{i}}\ip{L_{i}}{U_{-}^{0}}\\
 & =\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\dyad{R_{i}}{L_{i}}\right)\ket{U_{+}^{0}}+\left(\sum_{i=k+1}^{m}\dyad{R_{i}}{L_{i}}\right)\ket{U_{-}^{0}}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

which is similar to the smooth case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the PDE is not satisfied on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th characteristic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $x/t=\lambda_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, the jump condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{k}\Delta_{k}\ket{U}=\Delta_{k}\ket{F}
\]

\end_inset

and the entropy condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\lambda_{k}(-)=s_{k} & =\lambda_{k}(+)\\
\lambda_{k-1}(-)<s_{k} & <\lambda_{k+1}(+)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

are satisfied, in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}s_{k} & =\lambda_{k}\\
\Delta_{k}\ket{U} & =\dyad{R_{k}}{L_{k}}\left(\ket{U_{+}^{0}}-\ket{U_{-}^{0}}\right)\\
\Delta_{k}\ket{F} & =\Mat{A}\Delta_{k}\ket{U}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

They are all contact discontinuities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
RP for Single Conservation Law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The disturbance of the initial discontinuity spreads at a finite speed,
 so there must be two undisturbed regions in the solution, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,t)$
\end_inset

 takes its initial value.
 Such undisturbed regions are connected by a disturbed region.
 Self-similarity implies that the interfaces of these regions are straight
 lines emanated from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 So, the solution must have the following form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,t)=\begin{cases}
u_{-}^{0}, & x/t<a_{-}\\
u_{D}(x/t), & x/t\in[a_{-},a_{+}]\\
u_{+}^{0}, & x/t>a_{+}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(u)=\pdv{f(u)}{u}\qquad a_{\pm}=a\left(u_{\pm}^{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Our task is to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{D}(x/t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Shock Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(u)=a'(u)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}^{0}>u_{+}^{0}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(u)=a'(u)<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}^{0}<u_{+}^{0}$
\end_inset

, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{-}>a_{+}
\]

\end_inset

which means the characteristic curves emanating from the left half of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis will 
\emph on
run into
\emph default
 those emanating from the right half of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis.
 In this case, a 
\noun on
shock wave
\noun default
 separating the two families of parallel characteristic curves will emanate
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 The speed of the shock wave is determined by the jump condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\frac{f\left(u_{+}^{0}\right)-f\left(u_{-}^{0}\right)}{u_{+}^{0}-u_{-}^{0}}
\]

\end_inset

and the entropy condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{-}>s>a_{+}
\]

\end_inset

is strictly satisfied.
 The complete solution is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,t)=\begin{cases}
u_{-}^{0}, & x/t<s\\
\text{shock wave}, & x/t=s\\
u_{+}^{0}, & x/t>s
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Centered Expansion Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(u)=a'(u)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}^{0}<u_{+}^{0}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(u)=a'(u)<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}^{0}>u_{+}^{0}$
\end_inset

, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{-}<a_{+}
\]

\end_inset

which means the two families of characteristic curves will 
\emph on
diverge
\emph default
 from each other.
 In this case, a fan-shaped 
\noun on
centered expansion wave
\noun default
 separating the two families of parallel characteristic curves will start
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 The speed of the 
\noun on
wave head
\noun default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{+}$
\end_inset

, while that of the 
\noun on
wave tail
\noun default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{-}$
\end_inset

.
 In the region between them, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is smooth enough to satisfy the PDE, which can be solved from the equation
 of characteristic curves:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x/t=a(u)\implies u(x,t)=a^{-1}(x/t)
\]

\end_inset

The complete solution is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,t)=\begin{cases}
u_{-}^{0}, & x/t<a_{-}\\
a^{-1}(x/t), & x/t\in\left[a_{-},a_{+}\right]\\
u_{+}^{0}, & x/t>a_{+}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Contact Discontinuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There might be such a case that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{-}=a_{+}
\]

\end_inset

even though
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{-}^{0}\ne u_{+}^{0}
\]

\end_inset

In such case, there will be no mass/momentum/energy flowing across the discontin
uity, thus it is called a 
\noun on
contact discontinuity
\noun default
.
 The speed of the contact discontinuity is the same as the left and right
 characteristic speed:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{-}=s=a_{+}
\]

\end_inset

The complete solution is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x,t)=\begin{cases}
u_{-}^{0}, & x/t<s\\
\text{contact discontinuity}, & x/t=s\\
u_{+}^{0}, & x/t>s
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
A contact discontinuity can be seen as a limit case of a shock wave, since
 it is indeed a discontinuity, across which, the jump condition and the
 entropy condition are satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
A contact discontinuity can also be seen as a limit case of a centered expansion
 wave, when the angle of the fan-shaped region tends to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
RP for Conservation Law System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
The self-similar solution of an RP for a system of conservation laws has
 the following structure: it contains 
\begin_inset Formula $(m+1)$
\end_inset

 constant regions, which are connected by 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 elementary waves, each of which might be a shock wave, a centered expansion
 wave, or a contact discontinuity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
There are 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 characteristic fields, so the initial discontinuity will be carried by
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 elementary waves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since the solution of an RP is self-similar, we can define the slope as
 a new independent variable:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha:=x/t\implies\pdv{t}=\pdv{\alpha}{t}\dv{\alpha}\qquad\pdv{x}=\pdv{\alpha}{x}\dv{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset

PDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuasilinearHyperbolicSystem1d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be transformed into
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{t}\left(\Mat{A}-\alpha\Mat{I}\right)\dv{\ket{U}}{\alpha}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset

which implies in smooth regions, either one of the following two cases must
 be true: 1) 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{\ket{U}}{\alpha}=\ket{0}$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 2) 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Mat{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{\ket{U}}{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding right eigenvector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $(m+1)$
\end_inset

 constant states as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}\ket{U_{(0)+}}\\
\vdots\\
\ket{U_{(k-1)+}}\\
\vdots\\
\ket{U_{(m)+}}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\ket{U_{(1)-}}\\
\vdots\\
\ket{U_{(k)-}}\\
\vdots\\
\ket{U_{(m+1)-}}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
A shock wave or a expansion wave can only be carried by a genuinely nonlinear
 field, while a linearly degenerated field can only carry a contact discontinuit
y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Shock Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th characteristic field is genuinely nonlinear, there might be such a case
 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)-}\right)>\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)+}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, this means the characteristic curves on both sides of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary wave 
\emph on
run into each other
\emph default
, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary wave is a shock wave.
 Physically, there are mass/momentum/energy flowing across the wave with
 entropy increasing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{F}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the jump condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\ket{U_{(k)+}}-\ket{U_{(k)-}}\right)s_{k}=\ket{F\left(U_{(k)+}\right)}-\ket{F\left(U_{(k)-}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the speed of the shock wave, which is also the slope of the shock wave
 path.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entropy condition is satisfied with strict unequal signs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)-}\right)>s_{k}>\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)+}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Centered Expansion Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th characteristic field is genuinely nonlinear, there might be such a case
 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{k-1}\left(U_{(k)-}\right)<\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)-}\right)<\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)+}\right)<\lambda_{k+1}\left(U_{(k)+}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, this means the characteristic curves on both sides of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary wave 
\emph on
run away from each other
\emph default
, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary wave is a centered expansion wave.
 Inside the wave, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-characteristic curves must diverse from each other:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{\lambda_{k}(\alpha)}{\alpha}\ge0\qquad\alpha\in[a_{-},a_{+}]
\]

\end_inset

in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{-}=\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)-}\right)\qquad a_{+}=\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)+}\right)
\]

\end_inset

are the speed of the wave head and the wave tail, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A centered expansion wave is a smooth region, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=x/t$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Mat{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{\ket{U}}{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding right eigenvector.
 So, the 
\begin_inset Formula $(m-1)$
\end_inset

 generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Riemann invariants are constants across wave:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{W}{\alpha}=\ip{\grad{\phi}}{\dv{U}{\alpha}}=\ip{\grad{\phi}}{R_{k}}=0
\]

\end_inset

which can be used to determine state inside the wave:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(U_{(k)-}\right)=W(U(\alpha))=W\left(U_{(k)+}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Contact Discontinuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th characteristic field is linearly degenerate, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}(U)$
\end_inset

 does not change with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{k-1}\left(U_{(k)-}\right)<\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)-}\right)=\lambda_{k}\left(U_{(k)+}\right)<\lambda_{k+1}\left(U_{(k)+}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, this means the characteristic curves on both sides of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary wave 
\emph on
run parallel with each other
\emph default
, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary wave is a contact discontinuity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Physically, there is no mass/momentum/energy flowing across a contact discontinu
ity, thus no entropy increasing.
 The jump condition and the entropy condition are satisfied automatically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A contact discontinuity can also be seen as a limit case of a centered expansion
 wave, when the angle of the fan-shaped region tends to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 So, the 
\begin_inset Formula $(m-1)$
\end_inset

 generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Riemann invariants are constants across wave:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{W}{\alpha}=\ip{\grad{\phi}}{\dv{U}{\alpha}}=\ip{\grad{\phi}}{R_{k}}=0
\]

\end_inset

which can be used to connect states on both sides of the wave:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(U_{(k)-}\right)=W\left(U_{(k)+}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

